RECIPE DATA COLLECTION AND API DEVELOPMENT

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PROJECT OBJECTIVE

This project was developed to parse recipe data from a JSON file, store it in a MySQL database, and build REST APIs to manage and query the stored recipes.

The key objectives of this project were:

➤ Parse structured JSON data
➤ Store data into a relational database
➤ Implement RESTful APIs
➤ Apply validation and business logic
➤ Prevent duplicate entries
➤ Maintain clean layered architecture

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PROJECT ARCHITECTURE

The application follows a layered architecture:

Controller ➜ Service ➜ Repository ➜ Database

➤ Controller
Handles incoming HTTP requests and returns JSON responses.

➤ Service
Contains business logic such as validation and calculation of total_time.

➤ Repository
Manages database operations and data persistence.

➤ Database
MySQL database used to store recipe records.

This structure ensures separation of concerns, maintainability, and scalability.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

JSON PARSING AND DATA LOADING

The recipe dataset (US_recipes_null.json) is placed inside the resources folder.

To automatically load data during application startup, a class implementing CommandLineRunner was created.

Processing Flow:

✔ Application starts
✔ JSON file is read using InputStream
✔ ObjectMapper converts JSON into Java objects
✔ Recipe objects are extracted
✔ total_time is calculated using:

total_time = prep_time + cook_time

✔ Duplicate titles are checked
✔ Valid records are inserted into the database

This ensures:

✓ Automatic data initialization
✓ Data consistency
✓ No duplicate records

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

DATABASE DESIGN

Database Name: recipe_db

Table Name: recipes

Table Fields:

◆ id — Primary Key (Auto Increment)
◆ title — Recipe name
◆ cuisine — Cuisine type
◆ rating — User rating
◆ prep_time — Preparation time
◆ cook_time — Cooking time
◆ total_time — Calculated field
◆ description — Recipe description
◆ nutrients — Stored in JSON format
◆ serves — Number of servings

Note: total_time is calculated in the application to maintain data accuracy instead of relying on JSON input.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

REST API IMPLEMENTATION

Base URL
http://localhost:8080/recipes

────────────────────────────────────

A. POST /recipes

Purpose:
Add a new recipe to the database.

Validation Rules:

● title must be provided
● cuisine must be provided
● prep_time must be provided
● cook_time must be provided

Business Logic:

✔ Automatically calculates total_time
✔ Checks for duplicate recipe titles
✔ Returns appropriate HTTP status codes

Response Codes:

✔ 201 CREATED — Recipe saved successfully
✔ 400 BAD REQUEST — Missing required fields
✔ 409 CONFLICT — Duplicate recipe title

────────────────────────────────────

B. GET /recipes

Purpose:
Retrieve all recipes stored in the database.

Returns:
List of all recipes in JSON format.

────────────────────────────────────

C. GET /recipes/top

Purpose:
Retrieve top-rated recipes.

Query Parameter:

● limit (optional, default = 5)

Example:
http://localhost:8080/recipes/top?limit=2

Logic:

✔ Sort recipes by rating in descending order
✔ Return only the specified number of records

Response Format:

{
"data": [ top rated recipes ]
}

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

APPLICATION FLOW

Startup Flow:

1 ➜ Application starts
2 ➜ Database connection established
3 ➜ JSON file parsed
4 ➜ total_time calculated
5 ➜ Duplicate recipes skipped
6 ➜ Data inserted into database
7 ➜ Server runs at http://localhost:8080

API Request Flow:

Client ➜ Controller ➜ Service ➜ Repository ➜ Database ➜ JSON Response

